# CODEOWNERS — automatic reviewer assignment for security-sensitive
# and load-bearing paths.
#
# Format reference: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositories-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners
#
# How this file is enforced:
#
#   - GitHub auto-requests reviews from the listed owners when a PR
#     touches a matching path.
#   - The branch-protection ruleset on `main` does NOT currently set
#     `require_code_owner_reviews: true` (it's `false` per
#     `docs/ci/branch-protection.md`'s `gh api` payload). Owner review
#     is therefore advisory — a request that helps route attention,
#     not a hard gate. Operators may flip the flag later if review
#     burden allows; doing so makes every CODEOWNERS entry below a
#     blocking reviewer for its matched paths.
#
# Operator setup:
#
#   The team slugs below are placeholders. Before this file does any
#   work, an operator must create the corresponding GitHub teams under
#   the `buildwithbarista` org and add maintainers to them. The slug
#   namespace is `@buildwithbarista/<team>`; until the teams exist,
#   GitHub silently ignores entries whose owner is an unknown team
#   (the path matches but no review is requested), so populating this
#   file ahead of team creation is safe.
#
#   Suggested teams to create (replicated across all four public repos):
#     - `@buildwithbarista/security`     — owns CI/security config,
#                                          gitleaks rules, semgrep rules,
#                                          deny.toml, security-agent config.
#     - `@buildwithbarista/build`        — owns build-system manifests:
#                                          Cargo.toml(s), barback/pom.xml,
#                                          rust-toolchain.toml, .tool-versions.
#     - `@buildwithbarista/docs`         — owns architecture/compat/perf
#                                          documentation under `docs/`.
#     - `@buildwithbarista/maintainers`  — catch-all fallback (last entry,
#                                          last-match-wins per GitHub).
#
# Last-match-wins semantics:
#
#   GitHub evaluates patterns top-to-bottom and the LAST matching line
#   wins. Order matters: most-general patterns at the top, most-specific
#   at the bottom. The fallback `*` entry, if present, must be near the
#   top so per-path overrides take precedence.
#
# Pattern syntax:
#
#   `path/`     — directory and everything under it
#   `path/*`    — files directly in `path/`, not subdirs
#   `path/**`   — `path/` and everything under it (same as `path/`)
#   `*.ext`     — any file with extension `.ext`, anywhere
#   Leading `/` anchors to the repository root.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Fallback — every path not matched below routes here.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

*                                                @buildwithbarista/maintainers

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Security-sensitive surfaces.
#
# Edits to any of these can change the project's security posture
# without changing source code (e.g., loosening a Semgrep rule, adding
# a gitleaks allowlist entry, dropping a required status check from
# the auto-remediation guardrails). They are owned by the security
# team so the change is reviewed by someone who has the full context
# for that surface.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# CI workflows, action pinning, and the auto-remediation agent's
# entire config substrate (prompt, allowed-tools, guardrails YAML).
/.github/                                        @buildwithbarista/security

# Custom Semgrep rule pack — adding or weakening a rule directly
# affects what SAST catches on PRs.
/.semgrep/                                       @buildwithbarista/security

# cargo-deny + cargo-audit config — license bans, advisory ignores,
# source registry allowlists. Loosening any of these is a supply-chain
# decision.
/deny.toml                                       @buildwithbarista/security

# Secret-scan configs — gitleaks rules + per-finding allowlists.
# Adding an entry to `.gitleaksignore` says "this matching string is
# OK to commit" and must be reviewed by security.
/.gitleaks.toml                                  @buildwithbarista/security
/.gitleaksignore                                 @buildwithbarista/security
/.semgrepignore                                  @buildwithbarista/security

# Pre-commit + security-relevant docs at the repo root.
/.pre-commit-config.yaml                         @buildwithbarista/security
/SECURITY.md                                     @buildwithbarista/security

# Operator-facing CI/security documentation. Edits here change the
# operator's setup procedure for branch protection / DCO / etc.
/docs/ci/                                        @buildwithbarista/security

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Build-system surfaces.
#
# Edits to these manifests can pull in new dependencies, change MSRV,
# move JDK / Maven baselines, or alter the workspace topology. They
# are owned by the build team so dependency additions go through the
# Sonatype-MCP check documented in `CONTRIBUTING.md`.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Rust workspace + crate manifests.
/Cargo.toml                                      @buildwithbarista/build
/Cargo.lock                                      @buildwithbarista/build
/crates/**/Cargo.toml                            @buildwithbarista/build
/rust-toolchain.toml                             @buildwithbarista/build

# Java daemon build.
/barback/pom.xml                                 @buildwithbarista/build

# Toolchain pinning consumed by asdf and the docs.
/.tool-versions                                  @buildwithbarista/build

# Release configuration.
/.github/workflows/release.yml                   @buildwithbarista/security @buildwithbarista/build

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Documentation surfaces.
#
# Architecture / compatibility / performance docs are the project's
# externally-visible promises. Edits should be reviewed by the docs
# team so language and scope claims stay consistent.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/docs/arch/                                      @buildwithbarista/docs
/docs/compat/                                    @buildwithbarista/docs
/docs/perf/                                      @buildwithbarista/docs
/docs/efficiency/                                @buildwithbarista/docs
/docs/book/                                      @buildwithbarista/docs
/README.md                                       @buildwithbarista/docs
/CONTRIBUTING.md                                 @buildwithbarista/docs
/CHANGELOG.md                                    @buildwithbarista/docs
/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md                              @buildwithbarista/docs

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Licensing — the dual-license posture is a foundational legal commitment.
# Changes go through both security and maintainers.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/LICENSE-MIT                                     @buildwithbarista/security @buildwithbarista/maintainers
/LICENSE-APACHE                                  @buildwithbarista/security @buildwithbarista/maintainers

# This file itself — recursive ownership.
/.github/CODEOWNERS                              @buildwithbarista/security @buildwithbarista/maintainers
